2026-04-16 12:12:34 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module switch / its series wiring'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show 12 V present at the power-supply output and at the control-module input pair. One side of the control switch is at 12 V while the other side and the outgoing “+” to the load sit at ~0.36 V, with the return at 0 V. Thus essentially the entire 12 V is dropping across the control module (across the switch path), and no usable voltage reaches the load (only a weak ~0.36 V). The red ‘inverted cables’ LED is off, and the polarity from supply to control input is correct, so the control LED circuit is not clamping the line. This behavior is consistent with a faulty/high-resistance series path in the control module—most likely a defective or miswired control switch (e.g., failed contacts, internal open, or bad solder joint) or wiring immediately in series with it—rather than an error in inter-module cabling or the load module. Replacing/repairing the control-module switch and its series conductor should restore close to the full 12 V to the load when the switch is ON and allow the lamp to operate.'
